When dealing with fonts at different sizes, you have two primary options:

1. Store fonts with sizes in the map.
2. Store a single font and resize on demand.

The first option is more performant if you're using the font at multiple predefined sizes throughout your application, as it avoids reloading the font at different sizes repeatedly. The second option is simpler in terms of storage, but it's inefficient if you frequently change font sizes because SDL_ttf would have to reload the font data from the disk.

For the first option, your key shouldn't be just the file path; it must also include the font size. In other words, you'd have a map where each key is a combination of both the file path and the size. Here's how you can modify your `ResourceManager` to handle different font sizes:

```cpp
class ResourceManager {
private:
    // Each font is identified by its file path and size.
    std::unordered_map<std::pair<std::string, int>, Font, pair_hash> fonts;

    // Define a hash function for the unordered_map keys, since std::pair doesn't have a standard hash implementation
    struct pair_hash {
        template <class T1, class T2>
        std::size_t operator () (const std::pair<T1,T2> &p) const {
            auto h1 = std::hash<T1>{}(p.first);
            auto h2 = std::hash<T2>{}(p.second);
            return h1 ^ h2;
        }
    };

public:
    Font& GetFont(const std::string& filePath, int size) {
        std::pair<std::string, int> fontKey = std::make_pair(filePath, size);
        auto it = fonts.find(fontKey);
        if (it == fonts.end()) {
            try {
                // The emplace function will construct the Font in-place and avoid unnecessary copies.
                auto result = fonts.emplace(fontKey, Font(filePath, size));
                it = result.first;
            } catch (const std::runtime_error& e) {
                SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, "Failed to load font: %s\n", e.what());
                throw;
            }
        }

        // This assumes Font(filePath, size) correctly loads the font at the given size
        return it->second;
    }

    // Make sure the rest of your ResourceManager class has proper handling for this new map.
};
```

In this example, the key of the map is changed to a `std::pair` consisting of the file path and the font size. A custom hasher (`pair_hash`) is provided to the `unordered_map` to correctly hash the `pair` keys because `std::pair` doesn't have a default hash implementation that can be used in `std::unordered_map`.

This way, when you request a font with a specific size using `GetFont`, the `ResourceManager` will return a reference to the corresponding `Font` object, loading and caching it if necessary.

Make sure your `Font` class can handle being created with different sizes because you'll have multiple instances of `Font` for different sizes of the same font file. If the size needs to be changed later, a new `Font` instance with the new size should be created and stored in this map.

In either case, you want to ensure that caching strategies don't consume an excessive amount of memory by keeping many sizes of fonts that are used infrequently. If that becomes a concern, you could implement a strategy for evicting seldom-used fonts from the cache.

If you prefer not to use `std::pair` or a similar approach for handling different font sizes, you will need a different caching strategy. Since you want to avoid storing the same font in multiple sizes, you can instead store each loaded `TTF_Font*` in association with its size inside a container in the `Font` class. Below is an example of how you might implement this:

First, modify your `Font` class to manage multiple sizes:

```cpp
class Font {
private:
    std::string filePath;
    std::unordered_map<int, TTF_Font*> fontSizes;

public:
    Font(const std::string& path) : filePath(path) {}

    ~Font() {
        for (auto& pair : fontSizes) {
            if (pair.second != nullptr) {
                TTF_CloseFont(pair.second);
            }
        }
    }

    TTF_Font* GetFontSize(int size) {
        auto it = fontSizes.find(size);
        if (it != fontSizes.end()) {
            return it->second;
        }

        TTF_Font* font = TTF_OpenFont(filePath.c_str(), size);
        if (font == nullptr) {
            throw std::runtime_error("Failed to load font at size " + std::to_string(size));
        }
        fontSizes[size] = font;
        return font;
    }
};
```

Now, modify the map in your `ResourceManager` to hold a `Font` object for each path, without considering the size:

```cpp
class ResourceManager {
private:
    std::unordered_map<std::string, Font> fonts;

public:
    TTF_Font* GetFont(const std::string& filePath, int size) {
        auto it = fonts.find(filePath);
        if (it == fonts.end()) {
            try {
                auto result = fonts.emplace(std::make_pair(filePath, Font(filePath)));
                it = result.first;
            } catch (const std::runtime_error& e) {
                SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, "Failed to load font for first time: %s\n", e.what());
                throw;
            }
        }

        // Access the Font object and get the TTF_Font for the desired size.
        try {
            return it->second.GetFontSize(size);
        } catch (const std::runtime_error& e) {
            SDL_LogError(SDL_LOG_CATEGORY_ERROR, "Failed to load font at size: %s\n", e.what());
            throw;
        }
    }

    // ... The rest of ResourceManager as necessary ...
};
```

In this setup, each `Font` object knows how to manage different sizes of an actual SDL font. When a size is requested that isn't already loaded, `GetFontSize` loads and caches that size. The `ResourceManager` maintains a map keyed only by file paths but provides access to different sizes of fonts through the `Font` object's management of sizes.

Keep in mind that storing a `TTF_Font*` for each size used can still take up quite a bit of memory, depending on how many sizes and fonts you load. If your application uses a large number of different sizes, consider adding logic to the `ResourceManager` or `Font` class to limit memory usage by unloading less frequently used sizes or implementing a more sophisticated cache eviction policy.

