This approach maintains the encapsulation of the `SDL_Rect` and only uses the `bool` flag internally while providing a clear mechanism to represent a `nullptr` rectangle situation with `Rect`.

In SDL's `SDL_RenderCopy`, the destination rectangle (`dstRect`) specifies where on the rendering target the source texture or sub-portion of the source texture should be drawn. If `dstRect` is `nullptr`, SDL will render to the entire target (which is usually the entire screen or window).

To allow for both specifying a destination rectangle and also having the option to render to the entire target, you can follow the same pattern you used for the source rect (`srcRect`) and make the destination rect (`dstRect`) a pointer as well. This would consistently give the caller the option to specify `nullptr` for either or both rectangles, which corresponds directly to the functionalities provided by SDL.

Here's how you can modify `Renderer::RenderTexture` to accept `nullptr` for both the source and destination rectangles:

```cpp
// Renderer class method to render a texture
void Renderer::RenderTexture(const Texture& texture, const Rect* srcRect, const Rect* dstRect)
{
    if (SDL_RenderCopy(renderer, texture.GetTexture(), 
                       srcRect ? &srcRect->GetRect() : nullptr, 
                       dstRect ? &dstRect->GetRect() : nullptr) != 0)
    {
        // Handle error
    }
}
```

Now, when calling this method, you can use `nullptr` for either `srcRect` or `dstRect` to tell SDL to use the entire source texture or render to the entire target respectively:

```cpp
// To use the entire texture and render it to a specific part of the screen
Rect destinationRect(50, 50, 100, 100);
Renderer::RenderTexture(texture, nullptr, &destinationRect);

// To use a part of the texture and render it to the entire screen
Rect sourceRect(0, 0, 50, 50);
Renderer::RenderTexture(texture, &sourceRect, nullptr);

// To use the entire texture and render it to the entire screen
Renderer::RenderTexture(texture, nullptr, nullptr);
```

By updating your method in this way, you provide a transparent interface that maps directly to the underlying SDL function. It's clear and flexible and allows your `Renderer` interface to handle all the possible uses of `SDL_RenderCopy`.
